Azure Regions are geographical locations that contain one or more data centers. Each region is designed to provide low latency and high availability to users within that geographic area.

Examples of regions include East US, West Europe, and Central India.

Choosing the right region is important for performance, compliance, and cost considerations.

For example, an Indian company should ideally deploy its application in the Central India or South India region to ensure faster response times for local users.

A real-life use case is data residency compliance. Some countries require data to be stored within their borders. By selecting an appropriate Azure region, organizations can meet these legal requirements.

Another example is global applications like Netflix or Amazon. They deploy services in multiple regions to ensure users get fast and reliable access regardless of their location.

Regions also support redundancy through paired regions, ensuring data is replicated for disaster recovery.
